{"id":14881586,"mediaExerciseId":"7845cc17-b930-44f7-b4e4-9ef7e91c3e1d","exerciseName":"5","chapterName":"17","chapterTitle":"Dividends and Payout Policy","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"17.5","sectionTitle":"A Resolution of Real-World Factors?","pageNumber":585,"solutions":[{"id":6004002,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This exercise requires us to determine the reaction of the market to the unexpected dividend changes and define the dividend clientele.","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"## Requirement 17.5a\n\nThe market's reaction to the unexpected dividend changes is called **information content effect.** The stock prices increase when dividend unexpectedly increases. \n\nOn the contrary, when the dividend unexpectedly decreases, the stock prices also decline. The reaction can be linked to changes in the amount of future dividends predicted rather than a change in dividend payout policy.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/ab1e98b9a7304d9f076470500e665fd7/e8793541bcba4359cc84a42208586283/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/ab1e98b9a7304d9f076470500e665fd7/e8793541bcba4359cc84a42208586283/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"## Requirement 17.5b\n\n**Dividend Clientele** refers to the group of stockholders who share a similar preference about the company's dividend policy. They frequently make decisions about the distribution that gives them benefits or advantages. \n\n\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"Usually, companies with high payouts attract one group, and low-payout companies attract another. The common desired factors for high dividend payouts are brokerage and other necessary transaction costs, fear of consuming principle, and the desire for current income. Hence, a risky firm with significant but uncertain growth prospects would have a low dividend payout.\n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"See the explanation\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":28,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/ab1e98b9a7304d9f076470500e665fd7/afea667afcbb37a330b620cc7372e125/lateximg_large.png","width":259},"regular":{"height":14,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/ab1e98b9a7304d9f076470500e665fd7/afea667afcbb37a330b620cc7372e125/lateximg.png","width":131}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":true,"stepNumber":5}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"9b2f2c85-c90d-4fc6-9aa9-3ecccba1c181","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":5}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881587,"exerciseName":"6","page":589,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"b7505c0c-12d6-4f49-864c-edee21f4c123","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-1